portant as any epoch in modern history. This era, Beckley contends, will endure because the US has a much larger economic and military lead over its closest rival, China, than most people think and the best prospects of any nation to amass wealth and power in the decades ahead.Deeply researched and brilliantly argued, this book covers hundreds of years of great power politics and develops new methods for measuring power and predicting the rise and fall of nations. By documenting long-term trends in the global balance of power and explaining their implications for world politics, the book provides guidance for policymakers, businesspeople, and scholars alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aGreat powers. 0aHegemony. 0aUnipolarity (International relations). 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSecurity Studies. 4aU.S. History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh  aAmerican primacy.  aChinese weakness.  aPower.  aU.S. foreign policy.  abalance of power.  aculture.  acurrent events.  acyber security.  adefense.  adigital age.  adiplomacy.  adiplomatic relations.  aeconomics.  aeconomy.  aforeign policy.  ageopolitics.  agovernment.  ainternational security.  amilitary.  apolicymakers.  apolitical science.  apolitics.  arise of China.  asecurity.  asuperpowers.  aterrorism.  awar.  aworld powers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172479440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501724794423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501724794/original  a978-3-11-060655-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL